# Tracey Specification Workflow

Tracey is a specification traceability tool. Specs define rules using `r[rule.id]`
syntax. Source code links back with `// r[impl rule.id]` and `// r[verify rule.id]`
annotations. Tracey detects orphaned impls, unimplemented rules, and untested rules.

## File Layout

- Spec files live in `specs/*.md` (one file per concern).
- Tracey config: `.config/tracey/config.styx`.
- Impl annotations go in source files under `crates/**/src/**/*.rs`.
- Verify annotations go in test files (unit tests in `crates/**/src/**/*.rs`,
  integration tests in `crates/**/tests/**/*.rs`).

## Rule ID Conventions

Use short noun prefixes: `client`, `event`, `flush`, `chain`, `hlc`, `moq`,
`relay`, `backfill`, `auth`, `region`.

IDs use dot-separated levels with no depth limit. Use as many levels as
needed to be unambiguous, but keep each segment short.

```
r[chain.write.tail-ack]           ← good: short, specific
r[auth.jwt.alg.rs256]             ← good: deeper nesting for natural grouping
r[chain-replication.write.ack]    ← bad: use chain, not chain-replication
r[chain.replication]              ← bad: too vague, needs a detail level
```

## Writing Rules

### Granularity: one rule per observable behavior

Each rule describes exactly one observable behavior — one input/output pair,
one error condition, one state transition. Never bundle multiple independent
behaviors into a single rule.

```markdown
r[chain.write.tail-ack]
The tail node MUST append the event to its local log and then send an
acknowledgment back to the head.
```

Not:

```markdown
r[chain.write]
The chain replication protocol forwards events between nodes, fsyncs
them to disk, and sends acknowledgments.
```

### RFC 2119 keywords

Use strict RFC 2119 semantics: MUST, MUST NOT, SHOULD, SHOULD NOT, MAY.
Every rule contains at least one keyword. Be precise about what is required
vs optional.

### Spec hierarchy: leaf-level rules only

Specs define leaf-level rules. If a higher-level spec (e.g. `relay.md`)
references a concept covered in detail by a lower-level spec (e.g. `chain.md`),
the higher-level spec should contain a single rule pointing to the lower-level
spec rather than duplicating rules.

When existing overlap is found, prefer consolidating into the more specific spec.

### Error and fault coverage

Domain specs define their specific error and fault conditions: which failure
modes exist, what triggers them, and how the system recovers. Each distinct
failure path gets its own rule.

### Every user-visible error outcome gets a rule

For error/failure paths, write one rule per distinct user-visible outcome
or recovery behavior.

```markdown
r[chain.fault.mid-chain-failure]
If a chain member fails after the head has forwarded the event but before
the tail ack is received, the head MUST retry with a newly formed chain.
```

### Implementation-detail rules

Rules about internal implementation choices (constant-time comparison,
sharded maps, thread pool fairness) are allowed when they matter for
correctness or security. Accept that these may only have `r[impl]`
annotations and no `r[verify]`.

### Configuration rules

Security/correctness-relevant configuration parameters (token TTLs, retry
limits, rate limit thresholds) SHOULD have their own rules specifying the
parameter and its default. Cosmetic or purely operational configs do not
need rules.

## When to Create a New Spec

Create a new spec file when introducing a distinct concern — not per Rust
module, but per conceptual boundary. Ask: "would a developer need to
understand this as a self-contained unit?"

Examples of good spec boundaries: chain replication, MoQ integration,
HLC ordering, Postgres flush pipeline, backfill API.

Split an existing spec when it exceeds ~50 rules or covers two clearly
separable concerns.

## Annotation Format

### Impl annotations

Place `// r[impl rule.id]` on or immediately above the line(s) that
implement the rule. Multiple rule IDs can share one comment:

```rust
// r[impl chain.write.head-append] r[impl chain.write.fsync]
async fn replicate(&self, event: Event) -> Result<()> {
```

### Verify annotations

Place `// r[verify rule.id]` on or immediately above the test function:

```rust
// r[verify chain.write.tail-ack]
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_chain_tail_ack() {
```

### Placement rules

- Annotate the most specific code location, not a whole file or module.
- Prefer annotating the function/match-arm/branch that implements the behavior.
- One annotation per behavior, even if the code touches multiple rules.
  Put multiple `r[impl ...]` on the same line when they share a code path.

## Coverage Checks

Count coverage per spec:

```bash
# rules defined
rg -c '^r\[' specs/SPEC.md

# impl annotations
rg 'r\[impl PREFIX\.' crates/ | wc -l

# verify annotations
rg 'r\[verify PREFIX\.' crates/ | wc -l
```

Target: every rule has at least one `r[impl]`. Every rule that describes
externally observable behavior should have at least one `r[verify]`.
